    seoTitle: "ABG and Acid-Base – MLT Encyclopedia", seoDescription: "ABG interpretation: pH, pCO2, HCO3, respiratory vs metabolic, compensation for MLT exam.", seoKeywords: ["arterial blood gas", "ABG", "acid-base", "pH", "pCO2", "bicarbonate", "respiratory acidosis", "MLT exam"],
    overview: "Arterial blood gas (ABG) analysis measures pH, pCO2, and pO2 from arterial blood to assess acid-base status and oxygenation. Primary acid-base disorders are classified as respiratory (pCO2 abnormality) or metabolic (HCO3 abnormality), with or without compensation. ABG specimens must be collected anaerobically in heparinized syringes and analyzed within 30 minutes (or iced).",
    mechanismPhysiology: "Henderson-Hasselbalch equation: pH = 6.1 + log([HCO3-]/[0.03 × pCO2]). Normal: pH 7.35-7.45, pCO2 35-45 mmHg, HCO3 22-26 mEq/L, pO2 80-100 mmHg. Respiratory acidosis: elevated pCO2 (hypoventilation—COPD, respiratory depression). Respiratory alkalosis: decreased pCO2 (hyperventilation—anxiety, hypoxemia, early sepsis). Metabolic acidosis: decreased HCO3 (acid gain or base loss). Anion gap: Na - (Cl + HCO3). Normal 8-12. Elevated AG acidosis: MUDPILES (Methanol, Uremia, DKA, Propylene glycol, Isoniazid/Iron, Lactic acidosis, Ethylene glycol, Salicylates). Normal AG acidosis: diarrhea, RTA, normal saline infusion. Metabolic alkalosis: elevated HCO3 (vomiting, diuretics, antacid overuse).",
    clinicalRelevance: "Compensation: body attempts to normalize pH. Respiratory compensation: fast (minutes)—lungs adjust pCO2. Renal compensation: slow (hours-days)—kidneys adjust HCO3. Compensation NEVER overshoots (does not fully correct pH beyond normal). If pH is normal with abnormal pCO2 and HCO3: mixed disorder or full compensation.",
    signsSymptoms: "Acidosis: Kussmaul breathing (deep, rapid—metabolic acidosis), confusion, arrhythmias. Alkalosis: muscle cramps, tetany, paresthesias (decreased ionized calcium due to increased albumin binding at alkaline pH).",
    assessment: "Specimen: arterial blood in lithium heparin syringe, expelled air bubbles (room air pO2 = 150 mmHg → falsely elevates pO2 and decreases pCO2). Transport on ice if not analyzed within 30 minutes. Measured values: pH (glass electrode), pCO2 (Severinghaus electrode), pO2 (Clark electrode). Calculated values: HCO3 (Henderson-Hasselbalch), base excess, O2 saturation. Co-oximetry: directly measures total Hb, O2Hb, deoxy-Hb, COHb, MetHb—not affected by these interfering hemoglobins.",
    management: "Interpret ABG systematically: (1) Look at pH (acidemia <7.35, alkalemia >7.45). (2) Identify primary disorder (pCO2 or HCO3 abnormality matching pH direction). (3) Assess compensation (opposite parameter moving in expected direction). (4) Calculate anion gap if metabolic acidosis.",
    complications: "Air bubble in syringe: falsely elevates pO2 and decreases pCO2 (equilibration with room air). Delayed analysis without icing: WBC metabolism continues—consumes O2, produces CO2 (falsely decreased pO2, increased pCO2, decreased pH). Excess heparin: dilution effect, falsely decreased pCO2.",
    clinicalPearls: ["pH < 7.35 = ACIDEMIA; pH > 7.45 = ALKALEMIA—always look at pH first", "Respiratory disorders: pCO2 is abnormal. Metabolic disorders: HCO3 is abnormal", "Air bubbles in ABG syringe cause FALSELY HIGH pO2 and FALSELY LOW pCO2—expel immediately"],
    examPitfalls: ["Compensation NEVER overshoots—if pH is normal with mixed abnormalities, suspect a MIXED disorder", "Anion gap = Na - (Cl + HCO3); ELEVATED AG = acid being added (DKA, lactic, toxins); NORMAL AG = HCO3 being lost (diarrhea, RTA)", "Clark electrode measures pO2; Severinghaus electrode measures pCO2—know which electrode measures what"],
    faqJson: [{ question: "How to interpret an ABG?", answer: "Step 1: pH (acidemia vs alkalemia). Step 2: Primary disorder (if pH <7.35, look for elevated pCO2 [respiratory] or decreased HCO3 [metabolic]). Step 3: Compensation (the opposite parameter should be moving in the same direction to compensate). Step 4: If metabolic acidosis, calculate anion gap to determine cause." }, { question: "What is the anion gap?", answer: "AG = Na - (Cl + HCO3). It represents unmeasured anions. Normal = 8-12. Elevated AG means an acid is being added to the body (DKA ketoacids, lactic acid, toxic alcohols, uremia). Normal AG (hyperchloremic) means HCO3 is being lost (diarrhea, renal tubular acidosis)." }]
